    French Bulldog Dog Breed Information - American Kennel Club
    About the Breed The Frenchie is playful, alert, adaptable, and completely irresistible. The French Bulldog resembles a Bulldog in miniature, except for the large, erect 'bat ears' that are the breed's trademark feature. The head is large and square, with heavy wrinkles rolled above the extremely short nose.
    American Kennel Club
    French Bulldog | Description, Care, Temperament, & Facts
    The French Bulldog is a small counterpart of the Bulldog, but it has large erect ears, rounded at the tips, that resemble those of a bat. Its skull is flat between the ears and domed above the eyes, and the expression is typically alert, rather than morose as in the Bulldog.
    Encyclopedia Britannica
    French Bull Dog Breed Info - Petfinder
    Frenchies have a low center of gravity, wide body, heavy bone, muscular build, and large, square head with soft loose skin forming wrinkles about the head and shoulders. Entertaining home companions, these lapdogs are alert, with a curious expression, aided by bar ears, and unrestrained and free movement.

    French Bulldog behavior problems
    The French Bulldog is a small, muscular, and alert dog breed with a large, square head, short nose, and large, erect ears [1, 2, 5]. They are playful, affectionate, and loyal [4, 6, 8]. French Bulldogs are good with children and other pets, but they should not be left alone for too long [4, 6]. French Bulldogs are easy to keep and don't require much exercise [7]. However, they do require a lot of human interaction [7]. French Bulldogs are prone to many health concerns [7]. They are not the easiest breed to train, and some Frenchies take up to 8 months to potty train [9].

    Why are French Bulldogs so expensive?
    The main reason why French Bulldogs are so expensive is that the breeding costs are extremely high. For Frenchies to reproduce, they require artificial insemination & c-sections, which will cost the breeder anywhere from $1,000 to $3,000. And that's on top of all the other breeding expenses!Mar 12, 2022

    About

    Description

    The French Bulldog, French: Bouledogue Français, is a French breed of companion dog or toy dog. It appeared in Paris in the mid-nineteenth century, apparently the result of cross-breeding of Toy Bulldogs imported from England and local Parisian ratters. Wikipedia
    Life expectancy: 10 – 12 years
    Temperament: Bright, Playful, Sociable, Easygoing, Lively, Keen, Affectionate, Alert, Patient, Athletic
    Colors: White, Brindle, Fawn, Tan, Brindle & White
    Société Centrale Canine: standard
    Size
    Fully grown, the average, healthy weight for a French Bulldog is 16-28 pounds, and they stand approximately 12 inches tall at the shoulder. The average French Bulldog lifespan is 11-14 years, but life expectancy can be affected by many factors.

    Fun Facts About French Bulldogs - ASPCA Pet Insurance

    Allergy
    In dogs, rather than sneeze, allergies make their skin itchy. We call this skin allergy “atopy”, and French Bulldogs often have it. Commonly, the feet, belly, folds of the skin, and ears are most affected. Symptoms typically start between the ages of one and three and can get worse every year.

    https://4pah.com › client-resources › french-bulldog

    History
    The French Bulldog originated when English Bulldogs were bred with Pugs and Terriers after bull-baiting was banned in England in 1835. The smaller breed became a favorite companion for the Nottingham lace workers as the small Bulldogs loved to sit on laps and kept the workers warm.Mar 14, 2018
